<TEXT>
france has told new zealand it 
soon will start a new round of nuclear testing in the south pacific 
despite strong regional opposition a government official said 
today 
france has conducted 103 underground nuclear tests on the 
mururoa and fangataufa atolls since 1975 
deputy prime minister geoffrey palmer said he discussed the 
issue with prime minister michel rocard of france on sunday while 
the two were in the french territory of new caledonia for the 
funeral of slain independence leader jeanmarie tjibaou and his 
aide yeweine yeweine 
they were assassinated thursday on the island of ouvea 
palmer in an interview with radio new zealand said rocard was 
aware of strong regional sentiments against nuclear testing but 
that it was beyond his power to do away with the program 
disarmament minister fran wilde said rocards comments were 
unacceptable to pacific island nations 
there is an urgent need to stop the nuclear tests and the 
time to act is now she said new zealand will continue not 
only its strong opposition to the french testing program in the 
pacific but also its active promotion of a comprehensive test ban 
treaty 
