<TEXT>
the governing party declared victory 
early monday for its presidential candidate gonzalo sanchez de 
lozada who was poised in unofficial returns to upset former 
military ruler hugo banzer suarez 
no contender won an absolute majority in sundays balloting 
however so law required that the new congress select the president 
while banzer still held a razorthin and shrinking lead in 
unofficial returns the campaign chief of sanchez de lozadas 
party andres petricevic projected that he would win 29 percent of 
the vote to 27 percent for banzer 
the balloting was peaceful as voters in this impoverished nation 
stood patiently in lines to choose from among nine candidates to 
replace 81yearold president victor paz estenssoro who is 
retiring from politics 
voters also chose representatives for all 27 senate seats and 
all 130 house seats according to the constitution lawmakers must 
choose the president from among the top three finishers when no 
candidate wins more than 50 percent of the vote 
an independent television station the bolivian television 
association said banzer of the centerright nationalist democratic 
action party had won 278 percent of the vote and 274 percent for 
sanchez de lozada of the conservative revolutionary nationalist 
movement 
it based its computerized projections on a tally of 851437 
votes of the estimated 18 million cast nationwide 
jaime paz zamora of the social democratic movement of the 
revolutionary left was running third with 193609 votes or 227 
percent six other contenders trailed far behind 
banzers percentages slipped steadily from more than 30 percent 
in initial returns and another station american television 
predicted sanchez de lozada would pull ahead as more votes from the 
countryside came in 
banzer the frontrunner in polls was known to be strong in the 
cities where the vote was counted first while sanchez de lozada 
and paz zamora were counting on heavy support from rural areas 
where the vote was tabulated more slowly 
national election officials said they would not release any 
returns until at least midday today they said the complete count 
would take nearly three weeks as ballots trickle in from remote 
areas 
the new congress convenes on aug 4 and will have two days to 
decide on a new president who is to be inaugurated for a fouryear 
term on aug 6 
banzer had hoped for a convincing win by at least 5 percentage 
points to oblige congress to declare him president 
sanchez de lozada said he was confident he could win the 
presidency in congressional negotiations if he finished first or a 
close second 
even if banzer maintained his lead he ran the risk of being 
denied the presidency for the second straight time he finished 
first in the 1985 election but congress picked the runnerup 
estenssoro whose revolutionary nationalist movement had formed an 
alliance with the thirdplace movement of the revolutionary left to 
shut out banzer 
the election day calm was notable in what was once was south 
americas most politically volatile nation bolivia suffered 13 
military coups this century and had nine governments between 1978 
and 1982 
no serious violence was reported on sunday 
opposition parties made some complaints of fraud and 
authorities said three people were arrested for carrying several 
different identity cards apparently to vote more than once a la 
paz provincial official was arrested for voting twice officials 
said 
nonetheless election officials said they had no evidence of 
widespread irregularities and foreign observers said their initial 
impression was of a fair vote 
garcia pintos an uruguayan observer said voters are being 
provided with all guarantees we havent seen any sign of 
irregularities 
spirits ran high despite the long waits to cast ballots which 
were multicolored to help the 37 percent of the 67 million 
population who are illiterate 
this is a step forward for democracy said la paz 
businessman martin cariaga as he waited its another example of 
the maturity of the country 
banzer 62 seized power in a bloody coup in 1971 that toppled a 
leftist military dictatorship he ruled until 1978 when popular 
pressure obliged him to call elections 
banzer sanchez de lozada and paz zamora pledged to continue the 
governments battle against cocaine production and trafficking the 
united states provides about 55 million a year for drug programs 
to reduce coca leaf cultivation in bolivias jungles 
an estimated 300000 bolivians depend on coca leaf farming 
cocaine processing or trafficking for their livelihood government 
figures show coca leaves are the raw ingredient in cocaine 
