<DOCNO> AP890508-0079 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
university students fighting for democracy and 
clean government have taken a page from past chinese mass movements 
by heavily relying on dazibao big character posters to 
state their views 
the posters several feet long have gone up daily since april 
15 when the death of the reformminded former communist party 
chief hu yaobang touched off student demonstrations for more 
freedom 
because the news media is tightly controlled by the state the 
posters have emerged as a major means of expression for the 
students 
at first the posters largely praised hu who was regarded as 
sympathetic to calls for political reforms those who should not 
die have died said a poster at beijing university the nations 
most prestigious school 
more recent posters have discussed the achievements of the young 
student movement and debated what new steps students should take to 
press their demands after staging several prodemocracy marches 
that involved tens of thousands of people and a class boycott at 
universities throughout the city student activists are divided on 
what to do next 
at beijing university the main outdoor bulletin board is thick 
with posters pasted one on top of another in recent weeks some 
written by newly formed independent student unions and others by 
individuals 
some are hastily scrawled on newspaper pages others are long 
discourses written in a methodical hand on several pages of 
notebook paper 
cartoons have appeared on the posters as have songs including 
the beijing university pledge which begins in twofour time 
dont fear dont fear never be afraid 
hundreds of students workers and teachers read the new posters 
daily some furiously copy the messages in notebooks others read 
them into tape recorders and still others take pictures 
im doing this to maintain a historical record said a 
26yearold management student from the central china city of wuhan 
who last week was snapping photographs of beijing university 
posters 
in a few days they might be torn down by students who 
support the government he added 
authorities at beijing university and most other major schools 
so far have tolerated the posters which also have gone up on 
dormitory walls and on outer walls surrounding the campuses 
the beijing college of aeronautics however infuriated 
activists earlier this month by hosing down the posters a few new 
ones have since appeared including one written on a map of france 
with bold black chinese characters racing across the pyrenees 
bigcharacter posters seem to have lost the stigma attached to 
them during the 196676 cultural revolution when they were a 
principal source of the ultraleftist upheavals mass hysteria 
during the decade of turmoil posters of rival fanatical 
factions were plastered everywhere quoting from mao tsetungs 
red book and heaping abuse on unpopular superiors and 
government leaders in disfavor 
shoppers had difficulty finding the right store because some 
city streets were blanketed with the posters 
mao forbade any tampering with the posters no matter how 
inflammatory but they came down soon after he died in 1976 
deng xiaoping who soon emerged as chinas supreme leader 
showed his distaste for the posters when in late 1979 he ordered 
the removal of all political signs pasted on beijings democracy 
wall 
shortly thereafter chinas parliament removed from the 
constitution the right to put up dazibao 
the posters reappeared in late 1986 when students pressed 
demands for greater freedom and democracy 
but the official chinese media denounced the signs calling them 
dangerous cancers that student movement quickly ended when hu 
was fired and three intellectuals accused of inciting the students 
were purged from the communist party 
the official media has yet to criticize the current campaigns 
posters keeping in line with the leaderships conciliatory public 
stance toward the student movement 
newspapers have refrained from using the term big character 
poster when describing the signs in an apparent effort not to 
recall the dark days of the cultural revolution when posters 
provoked fear instead of thoughtful debate 
</TEXT>
