<TEXT>
atlantis astronauts 
glided out of orbit to a safe landing in the mojave desert today 
after a fourday mission that sent a robot spacecraft streaking 
through the solar system toward venus 
commander david walker guided the 97ton winged spaceship to a 
stop on a concrete runway at 1243 pm concluding a flight that 
covered 168 million miles and launched the first us 
interplanetary mission in 11 years 
congratulations and a nice landing and youve extended the 
shuttle reach far beyond earth orbit now magellan would be 
proud said mission control referring to the 16th century 
portugese explorer for whom the unmanned venus probe is named 
about 27500spectators the smallest crowd ever to watch a 
shuttle landing were on hand in 90degree heat the smallest 
previous crowd was 35000 in 1985 an estimated 460000 were here 
for discoverys landing march 18 a saturday 
an hour before landing walker fired braking rockets 184 miles 
above the indian ocean to drop atlantis out of orbit and start it 
on a blazing dive through the atmosphere on a course over the 
pacific and across the california coast 
two sonic booms crackled over the desert as atlantis swooped 
powerless through the clear sky making wide circles as it 
descended nasa selected a concrete runway because of crosswinds 
gusting up to 28 mph on two hard clay runways 
as the five astronauts ended the journey the magellan probe 
they released on monday was more than 640000 miles from earth on a 
15month 800millionmile voyage to venus to map its cloudveiled 
surface with supersharp radar 
scientists say the images should tell them about the history of 
venus and the evolution of its sister planet earth sulfuric acid 
clouds and a carbon dioxide atmosphere have had a greenhouse 
effect on venus with surface temperatures of 900 degrees and 
some scientists fear earth may similarly overheat 
on sunday the astronauts stayed up an hour past bedtime to stow 
equipment after replacing one of its four main computers which 
failed briefly in the only major glitch of the journey the 
computers actually fly the shuttle most of the time 
the problem posed no threat to the flight the shuttle has four 
computers a backup and a spare and can land on one computer but 
nasa decided to take no chances and had the crew cut short their 
experiments and install a spare 
the crew took 4 hours to install the computer and then got 
about seven hours of sleep 
we send our congratulations good work said mission control 
communicator tammy jernigan we wanted to point out that this is 
the first time that such a changeout has ever taken place on 
orbit 
