<TEXT>
safety tests on a candidate aids vaccine will 
begin soon in england an american researcher announced monday 
allan goldstein an aids researcher at the george washington 
university school of medicine said 24 volunteers are being sought 
in london to test the safety of a vaccine known as hgp30 
the volunteers he said must be free of any aids infection a 
second 24 to be used as a control group also will be selected 
goldstein said the purpose of the yearlong trial is to 
determine if the candidate vaccine is safe to use on humans 
earlier tests on laboratory animals did not reveal any problems of 
toxicity or other adverse effects he said 
control trials in the united states have not started goldstein 
said because the drug has not been approved by the food and drug 
administration for human experimentation 
hgp30 is a synthetic copy of a protein that is part of the 
internal structure of the human immunodeficiency virus hiv which 
causes aids or acquired immune deficiency syndrome 
in laboratory tests goldstein said hgp30 has been shown to 
stimulate the production of antibodies which attack and kill both 
the aids virus and cells in the body that are infected with the 
aids virus 
two other vaccines developed by other researchers are also in 
early safety trials according to an fda spokesman 
the main advantage to the hgp30 vaccine said goldstein is 
that the protein copy is based on a region of the hiv called p17 
that does not change the other vaccines are been based on proteins 
in the envelope of the virus a region that tends to change in a 
process called genetic drift because of this change vaccines 
based on stimulating antibodies against the viral envelope may not 
be as effective as hgp30 he said 
developing the hgp30 vaccine is still at a very early stage 
goldstein said it will be at least a year before the start of any 
clinical trials testing how well the vaccine actually prevents 
aids those trials he said could last for years 
goldstein said it will be at least five to six years before 
any aids vaccine is ready for general use and it could be much 
longer 
</TEXT>
