<TEXT>
the countrys first masscirculation 
independent daily newspaper in more than 40 years rolled off the 
presses monday with a masthead declaring there is no freedom 
without solidarity 
its editors gathered in jubilation to watch the press run at the 
state printing house which is normally used to put out the 
communist party and government dailies 
editorinchief adam michnik smiled broadly as he scrutinized 
the first issues of gazeta wyborcza or the election newspaper 
deputy editor helena luczywo obliged inkcovered printers who 
lined up and asked her to autograph copies of the paper 
its wonderful she said i cant believe it 
the newspaper obtained offices less than a week ago a lack of 
telephones in the office and the scarcity of newsprint in poland 
had left mondays publication up in the air as late as sunday 
morning 
communist authorities agreed to allow the opposition to publish 
its own daily newspaper during talks that ended april 5 
the government also agreed to legalize the solidarity 
independent trade union movement in return for the oppositions 
participation in polands first partially democratic parliamentary 
elections 
the first issue of gazeta wyborcza featured a frontpage picture 
of solidarity chairman lech walesa with a quotation in large type 
for it to be different and better we must win these elections 
the newspaper will publicize the oppositions campaign until the 
election on june 4 and then plans to continue as a daily with an 
opposition editorial viewpoint 
the first run was 150000 copies of an eightpage fivecolumn 
newspaper the editors hope to circulate 500000 copies by the end 
of the week 
only the first and last pages carried news the inside pages 
contained short biographies for all 261 solidaritybacked 
candidates running for the national assembly 
a frontpage note explained the newspapers aims saying 
here after more than 40 years of communist rule is a normal 
massprinted independent daily the first in poland and probably 
the whole soviet bloc 
in a probable first for a legally published newspaper here 
gazeta wyborcza instructed readers to tune in to usfinanced 
radio free europe to hear interviews with solidaritybacked 
candidates 
the newsstand price was high by polish standards about 8 cents 
because there was not enough paper to include ads the editors said 
