<TEXT>
borden inc pulled milk from stores in two 
southern states monday after learning that milk from some northwest 
louisiana and east texas dairies might contain traces of a compound 
used in rat poison 
borden the worlds largest dairy company pulled milk off store 
shelves throughout mississippi and in north louisiana 
gwen stewart of the louisiana department of health and hospitals 
said officials believe they kept all milk contaminated with 
dangerous amounts of barium carbonate from reaching store shelves 
the bottom line is there is not and has not been any 
contaminated milk on the market stewart said 
some milk with trace levels of barium was allowed on the market 
but it was considered an acceptable level she said health 
officials in mississippi agreed 
the amount you can drink is far less than the amount that 
would be dangerous said dr ed thompson of the mississippi 
department of health theres just not a significant health risk 
involved 
a person would have to drink about seven 8ounce glasses of the 
milk in succession for it to have any ill effect and more than 100 
8ounce glasses for it to be fatal thompson said 
there were no reports of anyone suffering any ill effects from 
drinking any of bordens milk officials said 
bordens spokeswoman chris tilton said they learned of the 
barium contamination on sunday and decided to voluntarily pull its 
milk as a precautionary measure even though tests indicated the 
amounts of barium present was below the acceptable level 
the problem first came to light when cattle died at an east 
texas dairy farm on april 22 and a louisiana dairy farm on april 
24 stewart said 
the milk was ordered held at the dairies and was not sent to 
companies for processing and therefore did not reach the general 
public officials said 
frozen milk samples taken after the withhold orders were given 
revealed the presence of barium from 2 parts per million to 5 
parts per million stewart said 
a check with a purina feed mill in shreveport revealed that feed 
used by the farmers had been carried in a rail car used to 
transport barium carbonate 
stewart said tests were done later at dairies and at plants that 
received milk from those dairies traces of barium less than half 
the maximum amount listed in government water standards were 
found in some samples stewart said 
barium carbonate is a white powder used in rat poison and a 
variety of processes including manufacture of some kinds of glass 
and ceramics according to the mississippi emergency management 
agency it is toxic if swallowed 
there are no standards set for barium in milk stewart said 
however she and tilton said government standards for water limit 
barium to 1 part per million 
after checking records purina told the state that contaminated 
feed had been sold to other farmers in the northwest louisiana and 
east texas area 
tilton speaking by telephone from bordens columbus ohio 
offices said the company did not know whether any of the milk ice 
cream and other products it distributed to stores was contaminated 
we made the assumption that this was in our milk supply she 
said 
purina picked up the unconsumed feed that went to louisiana and 
texas farmers and tests were being conducted to make sure milk from 
those areas was uncontaminated stewart said 
</TEXT>
