<TEXT>
a new agreement reducing the us military 
presence in spain should bring an end to an era of sometimes bitter 
relations between the two countries spanish officials say 
we have to recover all this wasted time said leopoldo 
stampa an adviser to spains defense minister i am very 
optimistic we have to relaunch our relationship based on this 
nuno aguirre de carcer a former ambassador to the united 
states said the end of negotiations brought a situation of 
normality in the relations 
the agreement accepts a spanish demand that the united states 
withdraw a highly visible air force fighter wing from the torrejon 
air base on the outskirts of madrid the capital the units 72 
f16s will be transferred over the next three years to southern 
italy 
the united states also is allowed under the eightyear pact to 
continue using three spanish military bases and nine communications 
posts 
the agreement reduces the authorized maximum number of us 
troops from 12545 to just over 8000 about 4000 are assigned to 
the torrejon base 
the accord replacing a fiveyear agreement was recently 
ratified by wide margins in both houses of the spanish parliament 
the two countries signed the texts of the new agreement in 
december ending several years of sticky bargaining 
carlos miranda director of international security affairs at 
the foreign ministry said the american decision to trim its forces 
in spain was regarded by the public as a kind of test 
spaniards he said have seen after this agreement that the 
united states is a country with which you can talk on equal terms 
the new levels set for us personnel represent he said what 
both countries feel is needed but not something imposed from 
washington to spain 
the spanish demand for removal of the 401st tactical air wing 
had angered us officials who were worried about finding a new 
location and paying for the move at a time of budget austerity 
moreover spain was seen as shirking its responsibility as a 
member of the 16nation north atlantic treaty organization the 
f16s comprise a crucial part of us frontline striking power in 
europe and are assigned to the defense of natos southern flank 
along the mediterranean sea 
italy has agreed to take the wing the relocation expenses will 
be picked up by nato except for housing and recreational costs for 
american troops 
in demanding the removal of the jets officials said the 
socialist government of prime minister felipe gonzalez was 
responding to public pressure 
in a march 1986 referendum a majority of spaniards voted to 
remain in nato but with conditions these included keeping spain 
out of natos integrated military structure maintaining a ban on 
nuclear weapons on its territory and reducing the us military 
presence spain joined nato in 1982 
the united states was given the right to use spanish bases under 
a military cooperation agreement first signed in 1953 during the 
authoritarian regime of gen francisco franco 
many spaniards still associate the us military arrangement 
with franco and argue it gave support and legitimacy to his regime 
with the removal of the fighter wing spanish officials said 
they have met the requirements of the 1986 referendum on reducing 
the us presence 
theres no reason why there should be further reductions 
said stampa 
the foreign ministrys miranda agreed 
the us presence in spain was excessive so there was no need 
of having the kind of presence we had he said and this goal 
has been attained 
in comparison with other west european countries spain has more 
us troops on its soil than greece and italy but fewer than 
britain and germany 
us forces will remain at bases in zaragoza moron and rota 
about 5100 us personnel are assigned to rota a naval base on 
the atlantic ocean in southwestern spain mostly providing support 
for the us 6th fleet in the mediterranean no us ships are 
permanently stationed there 
