<TEXT>
inside her house of glass joyce carol oates 
lives to haunt her readers writing books with all the anguish of 
thomas hardy and all the breadth of dickens 
outside her glasswalled house in princeton nj theres a 
different oates one who makes fewer demands one who really wants 
to be liked 
oates surprised her audience at a recent literary reading at 
russell sage college in troy just north of albany the audience 
knew of oates fascination with doubles and alter egos they also 
wondered how one writer could churn out two or more hefty books a 
year while teaching and lecturing but hearing her on stage they 
thought there really might be two joyce carol oates and that night 
they got the funny one 
she began with a terse cryptic piece that was over before the 
audience had a chance to really tune in there was a silence a few 
coughs no one was sure if literary etiquette allowed them to 
applaud 
if that means nothing to you youre very lucky oates said 
before moving on to a slightly longer piece i feel youre 
getting strength now and can handle longer work 
later when the audience did applaud she thanked them but 
added i assume youre applauding to hurry me up 
the audience had come to hear the bookish 50yearold princeton 
professor who has published 50 works since 1963 harsh and 
haunting and lyrical books in which used furniture salesmen fall 
victim to mccarthyism and suicide is always an option 
instead they saw a lanky woman who told funny stories 
when she first started publishing she submitted stories under 
the name jc oates 
i had the erroneous idea it was a world inhospitable to women 
writers she said editors would assume jc oates was a man 
maybe they were right in some symbolic way 
that leads to her fascination with doubles the worst day of her 
life was caused by her alter ego or the double who undone me 
oates says the double is rosamond smith the pseudonym she adopted 
to publish last years novel lives of the twins oates didnt 
tell her agent or her publisher ep dutton both were peeved 
i just wanted a new identity kind of a freshness to have a 
book come out where nobody was comparing it to other books she 
said in an interview you cant escape your identity thats very 
frustrating 
lives of the twins deals with twin brothers whose polar 
personalities merge as they fight for the same woman oates has 
written a second novel as rosamond smith being happily published 
by dutton which centers again on doubles soul mate due out 
this spring is about a princetontype professor involved with her 
opposite a charming ted bundyish psychopathic killer 
her latest novel american appetites takes place in a 
fictional town in new yorks lower hudson valley the setting is a 
camouflaged princeton and the main characters live in the same 
glasswalled house oates shares with her husband raymond smith 
like all her writing american appetites has an intensity 
and ferocity that disturbs readers the main character ian 
mccullough is tried for manslaughter in the accidental death of hi 
wife 
had he really thought she would be returned to him and their 
life would continue as always as if nothing had happened 
seizing her shoulders as he had in a paroxysm of murderous rage 
and throwing her backward helplessly backward into death into a 
sheet of glass 
a princeton colleague has called oates the fourth bronte sister 
while john updike suggested oates was born 100 years too late that 
she belonged amid a race of victorian wordeaters 
she has i fear rather overwhelmed the puny parsimonious 
critical establishment of this country updike writes 
she won the national book award for her novel them 
received the o henry prize for continuing achievement in the short 
story and is a perpetual nobel prize candidate 
even so critics complain about the complexity of oates work 
and her handling of traditionally male subjects shes been accused 
of writing like a man even of writing too much 
if theres a question oates hates its why so much 
violence in her novel wonderland a father kills his family 
before shooting himself in expensive people a young son plans 
suicide by gorging himself after killing his mother in 
bellefleur a vulture flies off with a bleeding baby in its 
talons and the heirapparent of a dynastic clan wipes out his 
family by crashing an airplane into their castle 
so why so much violence 
most writers have violence in their fiction oates says citing 
former princeton colleague el doctorows novel billy 
bathgate about gangster dutch schultz 
its much more violent than anything ive written she said 
but i notice in the reviews that doctorow gets theres never 
any mention of that i think thats because hes a male writer 
theres violence in oates ancestry oates grandfather died in 
a tavern brawl and her greatgrandfather killed himself after 
trying to shoot his wife 
oates grew up just outside the erie canal town of lockport ny 
her father frederic was an autoworker and signpainter her 
mother carolina a housewife 
fred oates a former amateur boxer got his daughter interested 
in boxing when he took her to golden gloves matches in buffalo in 
the 1950s the interest revived when she researched her novel 
you must remember this leading her to a friendship with 
heavyweight champ mike tyson and to ringside commentary at fights 
oates also wrote a booklength essay on boxing examining the 
sport not so much as athletics but as drama or dance 
felix stevick a character in you must remember this is a 
boxer oates research makes her feel as if shes been in the ring 
herself 
i really had to be in that mind that would naturally think 
like a boxer so i just imbued myself with it she said it was 
as if i had a lifetime partly as felix stevick 
filmmaker martin scorsese who memorialized boxer jake lamotta 
in raging bull has optioned the movie version of you must 
remember this 
as rosamond smith oates writes simpler tales of suspense books 
that might win her broader appeal but she doesnt believe shell 
ever have a huge following 
i dont think i could be a popular writer she said my 
writings too difficult bellefleur was a best seller but my 
secret feeling is that people bought the book and couldnt finish 
it 
</TEXT>
