management needs to understand what it takes to attract and 
keep intelligent people as secretaries says eleanor p vreeland 
president of katharine gibbs school inc managers have to 
recognize secretaries as an integral and productive part of their 
team and include them in the planning and goals of the business 
this will make secretaries feel like they have a direct link to the 
success of the business and will in turn reduce secretarial 
turnover 
there are 3 million secretaries in the united states 
representing the largest single part of the office work force 
salaries range from about 15000 to 30000 a year for this 
predominantly female profession 984 percent yet about 80000 
secretarial jobs a year remain unfilled the bureau of labor 
statistics projects that 400000 new secretaries will be needed in 
the coming decade making them the eleventh largest job category 
overall 
vreeland says the reason for high secretarial turnover is 
because so many managers dont consider the secretary part of the 
managerial team even though the average secretary shoulders more 
administrative responsibility and must have higher technical skill 
than she did five years ago 
by the l990s we hope the secretarial profession is what gibbs 
always envisioned it to be the secretary as a true part of the 
management team 
vreeland recommends that the manager improve his or her 
relationship with the secretary by conferring regularly about 
priorities keeping her informed about changes using her as a 
sounding board asking her to attend meetings and challenging her 
to grow through new assignments 
