outplacement process according to one of the countrys largest 
outplacement firms 
the firm drake beam morin inc of new york surveyed 116 
companies which use outplacement services and found that 96 percent 
rated the caliber of consultants as the most important factor in 
selecting an outplacement service program results and content also 
are important factors the survey showed 
the dbm survey shows that no matter how large a service 
company becomes its effectiveness is still measured in the quality 
of its individual client contact says william morin chairman 
and chief executive officer of dbm 
the cost of living in a new area is a big attraction in 
recruiting a top prospect advises one business consulting firm 
a great incentive for taking a job in a less expensive 
location is not having to spend as much of your paycheck says 
wallace j mcdonough executive vice president of runzheimer 
international a consulting company based in rochester minn 
using an average comparison of a 50000 income for a family of 
four mcdonough says that family would need 62116 to maintain its 
standard of living in a high cost area like boston but if the 
family moved to baton rouge it could live as well at 44020 a 
company should expect to pay more through costofliving 
adjustments to an employee going from a relatively inexpensive area 
to a high cost city he says 
runzheimer lists boston mass bridgeport conn honolulu 
hawaii and san diego calif as examples of locations that entail 
higher living costs low cost areas identified include san antonio 
texas spokane wash and charleston sc 
 
the ability to adapt to changes brought on by rapidly developing 
technology and business conditions is rated by students as one of 
the most essential skills for their worklife in the 21st century 
in a survey conducted by manpower inc a temporaryhelp agency 
based in milwaukee students also identified computer literacy and 
communication or people skills as being vital for their future 
job success 
the survey was taken among student temporaries placed by 
manpower 
the study also indicated that students believe they should 
become generalists with broad educational backgrounds and 
experience 
the students said they will need to be familiar with computers 
to manage information and automation they also say they are 
preparing themselves to communicate their technical expertise to 
coworkers and managers at all levels the acceleration of 
technological change in the office and plant has produced a 
plethora a new skills requirements accompanied by the need for 
adequate training says mitchell s fromstein president and 
chief executive officer of manpower 
push the jobhunting odds in your favor by making sure your name 
appears on one or more recruiting data bases advises a search firm 
that maintains such files 
colin a hanna of the cheshire group which maintains the bank 
executives network data base says employers are making use of 
these computerized resume files to lower recruiting costs 
he advises both active jobseekers and those who want to be 
alerted to opportunities to file their resumes with university 
alumni placement offices search firms employment agency networks 
government job offices and firms whose primary business is 
recruiting data bases only the last will charge for putting your 
resume into a data base 
 
with the job market leaning in the potential employees favor 
corporations must develop a marketing strategy to compete for the 
best candidates say two college marketing professors 
advancement opportunity tops the list of incentives according 
to a survey conducted on campus at miami university in oxford 
ohio by dr edwin simpson associate professor of marketing at 
miami and at san diego calif state university by dr thomas r 
wotruba sdsu marketing professor 
their study of 209 marketing seniors also indicated that a 
companys perceived financial stability and the opportunity for a 
new employee to express opinions rank high among reasons students 
would accept job offers 
other factors listed in preferential order were good 
communication job security the recruiters interest in the 
applicant low stress international opportunities whether the 
company entertained the student well american ownership of the 
company and whether an acquaintance worked there 
theres an overheating of the marketplace going on and 
employers really have to look at it as a selling situation says 
simpson 
bonuses or incentives are attractive items to students he adds 
but emphasis on commissions seem to have a neutral or even negative 
effect 
 
 
