<DOCNO> AP890508-0291 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
top exxon executives contradicted 
government witnesses monday insisting they repeatedly urged the 
quick use of chemicals to disperse the nations largest oil spill 
but that federal authorities turned them down 
their testimony before a fivemember subcommittee of the us 
house interior committee went against earlier statements by both 
the coast guard and the states top environmental official who 
said the oil company did not seek widespread use of dispersant 
chemicals to break down the oil 
exxon executives also disclosed for the first time that the 
cleanup has cost the oil giant 95 million to date 
we came to alaska to use dispersants exxon shipping co 
president frank iarossi told the panel i was pleading on my part 
to begin dispersal use we were very aggressive 
he said opposition from the state department of environmental 
conservation and the coast guard blocked the chemicals use or 
limited them to tests or only smallscale use 
were confidant that had we obtained prompt permission to use 
the dispersant the environmental damage of the spill would have 
been mitigated said exxon usa president bill stevens 
stevens said early use of dispersants or early burning would 
have broken up large amounts of spilled oil iarossi said the 
chemicals would have dispersed perhaps 40 percent of the alaskan 
crude oil 
dennis kelso commissioner of alaskas department of 
environmental conservation refuted that testimony and described 
exxons account monday as a fabrication dispersants in parts 
of prince william sound had been preapproved by the state even 
before the oil spill he said 
dispersants were not used extensively in the three days 
following the tanker accident because the winds and seas were too 
calm to provide the turbulence necessary to mix them with oil 
kelso said in a statement 
on sunday kelso said exxon and its pipeline service company 
alyeska spread disinformation by contending use of dispersants 
was sought kelso testified that exxon did not request permission 
to use the chemicals 
neither of them had the equipment on site to deal with it 
either through mechanical means or chemical means he said 
the subcommittee held two days of hearings to investigate the 
oil spill which occurred march 24 when an exxon tanker struck a 
reef outside normal shipping channels in prince william sound 
about 25 miles out of the transalaska oil pipeline terminal at 
valdez the tankers bottom was ripped open and it leaked more than 
10 million gallons of crude 
the former captain of the vessel joseph hazelwood 42 is 
accused of operating the ship while intoxicated and faces trial 
june 20 in valdez 
vice adm clyde robbins the no 2 coast guard official involved 
in the spill cleanup also testified monday that the oil industry 
did not seek permission to use large amounts of dispersants 
immediately after the spill 
robbins and the coast guards valdez commander both said exxon 
and alyeska did not urge the use of dispersants although tests on 
a small scale were conducted they proved inconclusive 
the issue of the dispersants is significant because alyeska as 
well as exxon has said the spill could have been contained more 
effectively if permission had been granted for the chemicals use 
the question of their use will likely play a major role in lawsuits 
stemming from the spill said rep george miller dcalif the 
subommittee chairman 
robbins also testified that exxon must put more work crews on 
the beaches if it hopes to meet a september deadline to clean up 
oil 
it appears they need to expand their resources in order to 
meet the fall completion robbins said he described the spill as 
one of the worst economic and environmental calamities this 
nation has faced 
i dont expect the beaches by the end of the summer to be 
squeaky clean robbins said but i would like to see some 
places that are clean and places where the impact of the oil is 
removed 
robbins is directly responsible for coordinating the cleanup 
operation reporting to coast guard commandant paul a yost jr 
president bushs emissary to the spill site 
exxon in a plan that has yet to win yosts approval has called 
for the worst of the oil to be cleaned off five islands in the 
sound by wednesday with 364 miles to be cleansed by sept 15 the 
leading edge of the floating oil has reached wide bay about 450 
miles southwest of valdez 
the subcommittee also heard from fishermen who said they fear 
their multimilliondollar catch in prince william sound will be 
reduced this season to protect seafood consumers from the effects 
of the oil 
at an estimated 84 million prince william sound has the 
nations eighthlargest commercial fishing industry said ken 
adams a fishing industry leader from cordova about 85 percent of 
the catch is salmon 
</TEXT>
